Can you illustrate what is CIDR Routing in VPC?
CIDR (Classless Inter-Domain Routing) is a method for allocating IP addresses and routing IP packets.
In a VPC, you define the IP address range using CIDR notation (e.g.,
typically in the format of x.x.x.x/y).
Example Explanation:
If you create a VPC with a CIDR block of 10.0.0.0/16, you can have IP addresses ranging from
10.0.0.1 to 10.0.255.254 for your resources within that VPC.
Generally, A CIDR IP looks like a normal IP address except there is a slash followed by a number in CIDR.
This part is called the IP network prefix. In VPC, CIDR block size can be from /16 to /28 in case of IPv4.
When you‚Äôre creating a VPC, you actually have to specify a range of IP address in form of CIDR just like 10.0.0.0/16.
This CIDR is the primary CIDR block of your VPC.
